\par }\pard\plain \s18\qj \fi454\li0\ri0\sb240\sa120\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid14049678 \f8\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\fs28\insrsid5640755 Managing the Web
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj \fi454\li0\ri0\sl-320\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f36\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\fs22\insrsid5640755 
Spiders' webs need constant management, because the spiral sticky part may be damaged by rain or by prey struggling to escape. Furthermore, dust sticking to the web may destroy the stickiness of the spiral threads.
\par A web may, depending on where it is, lose the properties which enable it to catch insects in a very short time \endash  24 hours even. For this reason the web is periodically torn down and re-built. 
The spider eats and digests the threads of the web it is tearing down. It will use the amino acids in the threads it digests to build a new web.}{\f0\fs22\up6\insrsid5640755 31}{\f0\fs22\insrsid5640755 
\par That part of the web which is eaten, and the time, differs according to the species of spider. Garden spiders, for example, do not touch the frame of the web, but just eat the radius of the web and the sticky spirals.
\par Tropical spiders construct their webs in darkness and eat them at dawn. Spiders in temperate regions eat their webs at night and build new ones for
 the day, because in these regions there are not as many night insects as there are in tropical regions. For this reason it is essential for the webs to be up throughout the day.
\par }{\f0\fs22\insrsid14049678 
\par }\pard\plain \s18\qj \fi454\li0\ri0\sb240\sa120\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid14049678 \f8\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\fs28\insrsid5640755 Building Webs to Suit the Prey
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj \fi454\li0\ri0\sl-320\slmult0\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f36\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\fs22\insrsid5640755 Spiders weave their webs to suit the size of 
the creatures they wish to hunt. The South American spider, for example, weaves a web with narrow openings that enable more easily to catch the white ants which come out to seek new nests in September. When it wants to hunt an insect such as a large butte
rfly it widens the openings and increases the web's strength and elasticity.
\par The angle of webs is also changed depending on the sort of prey that is expected to be caught (flying, walking, crawling, etc.). This both lessens damage and increases the trapping capacity.
\par }{\f0\fs22\insrsid14049678 
\par }\pard\plain \s18\qj \fi454\li0\ri0\sb240\sa120\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid14049678 \f8\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\f0\fs28\insrsid5640755 Warning to Birds and Camouflage
